        <tr class='athing comtr ' id='14335663'><td>
            <table border='0'>  <tr>    <td class='ind'><img src="s.gif" height="1" width="80"></td><td valign="top" class="votelinks"><center><a id='up_14335663' href='vote?id=14335663&amp;how=up&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D14335159'><div class='votearrow' title='upvote'></div></a></center></td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px;"><span class="comhead">
          <a href="user?id=lclarkmichalek" class="hnuser">lclarkmichalek</a> <span class="age"><a href="item?id=14335663">6 hours ago</a></span> <span id="unv_14335663"></span><span class="par"></span> <a class="togg" n="3" href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="return toggle(event, 14335663)"></a>          <span class='storyon'></span>
                  </span></div><br><div class="comment">
                  <span class="c00">Not all Intel CPUs have AMT. Most consumer machines won&#x27;t have it enabled, it&#x27;s an enterprise targeted feature.<p><pre><code>  &gt; Does this mean every Intel system built since 2008 can be taken over by hackers?
  
  No. Most Intel systems don&#x27;t ship with AMT. Most Intel systems with AMT don&#x27;t have it turned on.
</code></pre>
From an FAQ by MJG, the author of the tool we are discussing: <a href="https:&#x2F;&#x2F;mjg59.dreamwidth.org&#x2F;48429.html" rel="nofollow">https:&#x2F;&#x2F;mjg59.dreamwidth.org&#x2F;48429.html</a><span>
